<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="550" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,617,1830]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,689,714]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">Description.</emphasis>
Male (
<typeStatus box="[424,529,689,714]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">holotype</typeStatus>
). Size, coloration and external structure of body similar to those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1287,1388,690,713]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Varitrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striata">
<emphasis box="[1287,1388,690,713]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">V. striata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,249,727,750]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Varitrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tawau">
<emphasis box="[151,249,727,750]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">V. tawau</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but with some differences: anterior part of epicranium under rostral apex and under antennal cavities as well as nearest parts of genae darkened; dorsum of head with dark median area strongly narrowing on rostrum and a pair of small blackish spots near eyes (behind lateral ocelli); antennal flagellum and distal part of maxillary palpi more distinctly spotted; eyes with dark brown lower and light brown upper halves; pronotum with dark both median part of disc and upper half of each lateral lobe, and with rather numerous small dark spots on rest of this lobe (
<figureCitation box="[214,282,905,930]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[237,1352,199,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[232,1356,193,1879]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 9. Head and pronotum of male from above: 2, Varitrella orion sp. nov.; 3, V. trusmadi sp. nov.; 4, V. striata sp. nov.; 5, V. ro bu st a sp. nov.; 6, V. suk au sp. nov.; 7. V. tawau sp. nov.; 8, V. amoena sp. nov.; 9, V. manukan sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253149/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">
Fig. 
<number box="[267,282,906,930]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
); tegmina light (yellowish grey) with several dark spots in dorsal field (one at base, one near plectrum, one in region of chords, and larger longitudinal spot near lateral edge of apical area), with darkish stripes along medial edge of this field and around diagonal vein, with smaller darkish stripes in some other areas (latter stripes especially numerous in mirror and apical area), and with dark longitudinal band along upper edge of lateral field occupying also upper parts of membranes between Sc branches (this band partly divided into two dark stripes by yellowish humeral stripe and crossed by more or less light veins and veinlets; 
<figureCitation box="[1050,1134,1085,1110]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 15" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1821,1843]" captionTargetBox="[156,1434,197,1790]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1800]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 15. Left and right male tegmina: 12, Varitrella trusmadi sp. nov.; 13, V. striata sp. nov.; 14, V. tawau sp. nov.; 15, V. amoena sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253151/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">
Fig. 
<number box="[1103,1134,1085,1110]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
); legs with darkened most part of tarsi, few darkish longitudinal stripes on outer surface of hind femora, rather dark area in distal part of these femora, and dark both distal half of hind tibiae and ventral surface of rest of these tibiae; scape approximately 
<number box="[1387,1436,1157,1182]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="1.75">1.75</number>
times as wide as rostral apex; pronotum distinctly wider in posterior part (approximately as in 
<taxonomicName box="[1219,1320,1194,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Varitrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striata">
<emphasis box="[1219,1320,1194,1217]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">V. striata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and with almost obtusely angulate posterior edge of disc (
<figureCitation box="[734,809,1229,1254]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[237,1352,199,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[232,1356,193,1879]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 9. Head and pronotum of male from above: 2, Varitrella orion sp. nov.; 3, V. trusmadi sp. nov.; 4, V. striata sp. nov.; 5, V. ro bu st a sp. nov.; 6, V. suk au sp. nov.; 7. V. tawau sp. nov.; 8, V. amoena sp. nov.; 9, V. manukan sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253149/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">
Fig. 
<number box="[793,809,1230,1254]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
); tegmina with apical area of dorsal field very long (somewhat longer than in all previous species) and with venation as in 
<figureCitation box="[966,1050,1265,1290]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 15" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1821,1843]" captionTargetBox="[156,1434,197,1790]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1800]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 15. Left and right male tegmina: 12, Varitrella trusmadi sp. nov.; 13, V. striata sp. nov.; 14, V. tawau sp. nov.; 15, V. amoena sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253151/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">
Fig. 
<number box="[1019,1050,1265,1290]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
; central membranous area of anal plate distinctly transverse but not divided into a pair of more or less separate areas (
<figureCitation box="[1158,1248,1301,1326]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 31" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1764,1786]" captionTargetBox="[157,1433,196,1737]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1742]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 31. Varitrella, male: 20 – 22, V. orion sp. nov., stridulatory vein of right tegmen from below (20), abdominal apex from above (21), and genital plate from below (22); 23 – 28, anal plate partly from above and partly from behind in V. trusmadi sp. nov. (23), V. striata sp. nov. (24), V. robusta sp. nov. (25), V. tawau sp. nov. (26), V. suk au sp. nov. (27) and V. amoena sp. nov. (28); 29 – 31, genitalia of V. palawanensis (29), V. mindoroensis (30) and V. quadrata (31) from side and from below, with names of morphological structures. Abbreviations: ds, dorsal epiphallic spine; ec, ectoparamere; ea, endoparameral apodeme; en, endoparamere; ep, epiphallus; f, formula (= mold of spermatophore attachment plate); lo, lateral lobe of rachis; mr, median sclerotized ribbon fused with formula; r, rachis (= guiding rod); ra, ramus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253153/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">
Fig. 
<number box="[1216,1248,1302,1326]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="28.0">28</number>
</figureCitation>
). Genitalia with epiphallus slightly similar to that of all previous species but more curved in profile and without angular notches between dorsal spines and dorsal edges of more distal epiphallic parts (see in profile); ectoparameres well developed, short and strongly curved in middle part; rachis rather long, with long and strongly widened distal part, with a pair of very small and almost spine-like processes on lateral surfaces of this widened part (
<figureCitation box="[1289,1423,1445,1470]" captionStart="FIGURES 59 – 70" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[185,1390,202,1895]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[172,1416,193,1906]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 59 – 70. Varitrella, male: 59 – 62, V. tawau sp. nov.; 63 – 66, V. su k a u sp. nov.; 67 – 70, V. amoena sp. nov. Genitalia from above (59, 63, 67), from below (60, 64, 68) and from side (61, 65, 69); spermatophore (66, 70) and its ampulla (62) from side." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253155/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">
Figs 
<number box="[1349,1423,1445,1470]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="68.0" valueMax="69.0" valueMin="67.0">67–69</number>
</figureCitation>
); spermatophore with more or less globular ampulla (
<figureCitation box="[731,815,1481,1506]" captionStart="FIGURES 59 – 70" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1955,1977]" captionTargetBox="[185,1390,202,1895]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[172,1416,193,1906]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 59 – 70. Varitrella, male: 59 – 62, V. tawau sp. nov.; 63 – 66, V. su k a u sp. nov.; 67 – 70, V. amoena sp. nov. Genitalia from above (59, 63, 67), from below (60, 64, 68) and from side (61, 65, 69); spermatophore (66, 70) and its ampulla (62) from side." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253155/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">
Fig. 
<number box="[783,815,1482,1506]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="70.0">70</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,617,1830]" box="[199,400,1517,1542]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">Female unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,617,1830]" box="[199,1223,1553,1578]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">
Length in mm. Body 
<number box="[439,470,1554,1578]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="18.0">18</number>
; body with wings 
<number box="[676,707,1554,1578]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="29.0">29</number>
; pronotum 
<number box="[834,850,1554,1578]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="3.0">3</number>
; tegmina 
<number box="[960,1012,1553,1578]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="20.5">20.5</number>
; hind femora 
<number box="[1167,1218,1553,1578]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="11.5">11.5</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,617,1830]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1589,1614]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">Comparison.</emphasis>
The new species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[779,910,1590,1614]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Madasumma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mjobergi">
<emphasis box="[779,910,1590,1614]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">V. mjobergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Chopard" box="[1083,1265,1589,1614]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" refString="Chopard, L. (1930) 1. - The Gryllidae of Sarawak. Sarawak Museum Journal, 4, 1 (12), 1 - 42, pl. 1 - 8." type="journal article" year="1930">
Chopard (
<number box="[1198,1257,1590,1614]" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" value="1930.0">1930</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1339,1435,1589,1614]" name="Malaysia" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">Sarawak</collectingCountry>
State of 
<collectingCountry box="[245,348,1625,1650]" name="Malaysia" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
in Borneo (“Mount Dulit”), in the characteristic epiphallus. However, it is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Madasumma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mjobergi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">V. mjobergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of a pair of distinct dark longitudinal stripes running dorsally from inner parts of the eyes to the head posterior edge, presence of a dark median area on the pronotal disc, a clearly longer apical area of the dorsal tegminal field (this area is not shorter than a space from the stridulatory vein to distal edge of mirror; 
<emphasis box="[1358,1389,1735,1758]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="550">vs.</emphasis>
this area is distinctly shorter than the above-mentioned space), a somewhat shorter and slightly curved (in profile) epiphallus, and a more projected posterior part of the rachis in male genitalia.
</paragraph>
